Creating an AWS VPC (Virtual Private Cloud) manually is a fundamental task when setting up infrastructure in the cloud. Here's a step-by-step guide using the AWS Management Console (GUI). If you'd prefer a Terraform or AWS CLI version afterward, let me know.

üß∞ Prerequisites
An active AWS account

IAM user with permissions for VPC, subnets, route tables, internet gateway, etc.

üåê Step-by-Step: Create a VPC in AWS Console
1Ô∏è‚É£ Log In to AWS Console
Navigate to: https://console.aws.amazon.com/vpc/

2Ô∏è‚É£ Create VPC
Go to VPC Dashboard

Click ‚ÄúCreate VPC‚Äù

Choose VPC Only (or ‚ÄúVPC and more‚Äù if you want subnets and internet gateway together)

Fill in:

Name tag: My-VPC

IPv4 CIDR block: 10.0.0.0/16 (adjust as needed)

Tenancy: Default

Click Create VPC

‚úÖ Your VPC is now created.

3Ô∏è‚É£ Create Subnets
You typically create at least:

1 Public Subnet (with internet access)

1 Private Subnet (for backend services)

Create Public Subnet:
Go to Subnets ‚Üí Create Subnet

Select your VPC (My-VPC)

Subnet name: Public-Subnet-1

Availability Zone: us-east-1a (or choose yours)

IPv4 CIDR block: 10.0.1.0/24

Click Create Subnet

Create Private Subnet:
Repeat steps above with:

Subnet name: Private-Subnet-1

CIDR block: 10.0.2.0/24

4Ô∏è‚É£ Create and Attach an Internet Gateway
Go to Internet Gateways ‚Üí Create Internet Gateway

Name: My-IGW

Click Create Internet Gateway

Select the new IGW ‚Üí Actions ‚Üí Attach to VPC

Choose My-VPC ‚Üí Attach

5Ô∏è‚É£ Create Route Table
Go to Route Tables ‚Üí Create route table

Name: Public-RT

Select My-VPC

Click Create route table

Add Internet Route:
Select Public-RT

Routes ‚Üí Edit routes ‚Üí Add route:

Destination: 0.0.0.0/0

Target: your Internet Gateway (igw-xxxx)

Save routes

Associate Public Subnet:
Go to Subnet Associations

Edit subnet associations

Select Public-Subnet-1 ‚Üí Save

6Ô∏è‚É£ Modify Public Subnet to Auto-Assign Public IPs
Go to Subnets

Click Public-Subnet-1

Edit subnet settings

Enable Auto-assign public IPv4 address

Save

7Ô∏è‚É£ (Optional) NAT Gateway for Private Subnet Access
To allow private subnet to access the internet (e.g., for updates):

Go to Elastic IPs ‚Üí Allocate Elastic IP

Allocate

Go to NAT Gateway ‚Üí Create NAT Gateway

Subnet: Public-Subnet-1

Elastic IP: choose the one you just created

Create

Go to Route Tables ‚Üí Create route table ‚Üí name it Private-RT

Edit routes ‚Üí Add route:

Destination: 0.0.0.0/0

Target: NAT Gateway

Associate Private-Subnet-1 with Private-RT

‚úÖ Summary of Resources Created
Resource	CIDR / Purpose	Notes
VPC	10.0.0.0/16	Your private network
Public Subnet	10.0.1.0/24	For EC2 with internet
Private Subnet	10.0.2.0/24	For internal services
Internet Gateway	n/a	Enables internet access
Route Table	Public	Internet access via IGW
NAT Gateway	(optional)	Private subnet internet access

